Modeling Notebook for ESRI Practicum¶

In [2]:
from IPython.display import Image

In this part of our project, we are doing multiple steps to create and evaluate our models.

  1. Data Preparation
  2. Data visualization and analyze the data for feature selection and modeling
  3. Oversampling
  4. Feature Selection
  5. Splitting data into smaller dataset for Train and test
  6. Hyperparameter Tuning
  7. Creating some custom functions for model evaluation matrix as model is not balanced
  8. Run Model on sampled and non sampled dataset
  9. Collect the matrices
  10. Compare the matrices to select one model

Our team also identified the bug on the ArcGIS Pro with the `njob=1` parameter in the gridsearch. This was reported to ESRI; ESRI team will work with the Pro team internally to address this bug. If you want to run this notebook on the Arcgis Pro. Simply uncomment the below line and comment out the read_csv line.

We can see above that several of the columns in our dataset has very large number of null values.

  • We are removing the variables that have more than 90K null values as our datset has around 118K.
  • Also, we are removing some location specific variables such as lat, lon etc. as they will not be helpful in predicting the water point status.

We are doing feature selection later in the analysis after creating the dummy variables and after some cleaning up of data.

Data Preparation¶

Data Cleaning¶

These 3 functions are to clean up/modify the data. Water source is one of the most important feature in predicting the water point status. So, it is very important that we have a very clean water source column in our dataset.

There are 3 columns for the water source in our dataset -

  • water_source_clean,
  • water_tech_clean and
  • water_source.

Water_source has the lowest number of null values but the description of the water sources is very long, misleading and repetitive. Water tech clean and water source clean both have good description of the water sources. We wanted to have the less number of categories for the water sources without losing any information as we will be creating the dummy variables for this columns for our algorithms.

  • The first function tries to put the description of the water source from either water_tech_clean or water_source depending on which one is not null.
  • The second function clubs the same description water source in one category. For example - Shadoof Sahduf, Shahduf..etc will all be placed under Shadoof.
  • The third functions converts the categorized "yes"/"no" for the water point status into binary 1 and 0.
In [4]:
def water_source_cleanup_1(row):
    if pd.isnull(row['F_water_source_clean']):
        if pd.isnull(row['F_water_tech_clean']):
            return row['F_water_source']
        else:
            return row["F_water_tech_clean"]
    else:
        return row['F_water_source_clean']
    
def water_source_cleanup_2(row):
    if pd.isnull(row["water_source_sup_clean"]):
        return np.nan
    elif ("well" in row['water_source_sup_clean']) or ("Well" in row['water_source_sup_clean']):
        return "Water Well"
    elif row['water_source_sup_clean'].startswith("Shad"):
        return "Shadoof"
    elif "Spring" in row['water_source_sup_clean']:
        return "Spring"
    else:
        return row["water_source_sup_clean"]
    
def label_wp_status(row):
    if pd.isnull(row['F_status_id']):
        return np.nan    
    if row['F_status_id'] == "Yes":
        return int(1)
    if row['F_status_id'] == "No":
        return int(0)
In [5]:
# Call to the above functions to clean up and creates new columns for the water source and for the wp status
wp_ml_df['water_source_sup_clean'] = wp_ml_df.apply (lambda row: water_source_cleanup_1(row), axis=1)
wp_ml_df['water_source_sup_clean'] = wp_ml_df.apply(lambda row: water_source_cleanup_2(row), axis=1)
wp_ml_df['wp_status_label'] = wp_ml_df.apply (lambda row: label_wp_status(row), axis=1)

Oversampling using SMOTE technique to balance the dataset¶

Resampling for imbalanced classes¶

The highly skewed nature of this data presents a challenge in training a classifier. With such a small percent of minority samples, the majority samples will heavily weight the training data, and the final model will be likely to predict that any new sample is Functional.

The idea behind SMOTE is that in order to train a model that can accurately identify the minority class, you need a reasonably balanced training set. At a high level, SMOTE is used to generate new instances of the minority class using a set of similar, but not identical, minority samples from the training set. A minority sample is chosen at random, and then a new sample is generated using a linear combination of the k-nearest neighbors of the randomly chosen sample. Other resampling techniques merely duplicate some samples from the training set, but this does not add any new information to help fit a model to the patterns in the data. With SMOTE, the new samples are not merely copies of the training data, so they can add to the predictive power of the model in testing.

In [15]:
# find proportion of minority sample in data
def get_minority_proportion(y_vals):
    unique, counts = np.unique(y_vals, return_counts=True)
    cts_dict = dict(zip(unique, counts))
    majority_counts = cts_dict[0]
    minority_counts = cts_dict[1]
    minority_prop = minority_counts/(minority_counts+majority_counts)
    return minority_prop, minority_counts

# use SMOTE For oversampling minority class
def get_oversample(X, y):
    from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
    sm = SMOTE()
    X_over, y_over = sm.fit_resample(X, y)
    minority_prop, _ = get_minority_proportion(y_over)
#     print(f'minority proportion in oversampled data: {minority_prop*100:0.2f}%')
    return X_over, y_over

# standardize data
def scale_data(X):
    from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
    scaler = StandardScaler().fit(X)
    return scaler.transform(X)

Define Evaluation Matrix¶

The goal with this analysis was to determine the most effective method for identifying non-functional water point; in other words, to maximize the number of true negatives while minimizing false positives. In a highly imbalanced dataset such as this one, a model could classify all water points as functional and still achieve over 90% accuracy without finding any non-functional water points, but it would have little practical use. Generally, the cost of identifying a non-functional water point will be higher than the cost of not identifying a functional water point. However, false negatives do have a cost in our case. There are labor and other resources involved in reaching to the site to perform the water point evaluation. These resources and labor are waste if the water point is functional.

Thus, with our analysis, we needed an evaluation metric that balances recall with precision. F1 score is often used to achieve this balance, and we decided to use a variation on F1 score: the F-beta score. With this metric, a parameter is added to weight precision and recall depending on the needs of the model.

The formula for F-beta is:

F-beta = ((1 + $\beta^2$) * Precision * Recall) / ($\beta^2$ * Precision + Recall)

We set $\beta$ = 2, because recall should hold greater weight than precision.

This metric is known as the F2 score.

In [17]:
# f2 score: 2X emphasis on recall, vs precision (minimize false negatives)
def get_f_beta_score(precision, recall, beta=0):
    f_beta_score = ((1 + beta ** 2) * precision * recall) / (beta ** 2 * precision + recall)
    return f_beta_score


# function to evaluate model performance on testing data
def get_eval_metrics(clf_name, ytrue, ypreds):
    accy = accuracy_score(ytrue, ypreds)
    conf_mtx = confusion_matrix(ytrue, ypreds)
    recall = np.diag(conf_mtx) / np.sum(conf_mtx, axis=1)
    precision = np.diag(conf_mtx) / np.sum(conf_mtx, axis=0)
    f1_score = 2*((precision*recall)/(precision+recall))
    f2_score = get_f_beta_score(precision, recall, beta=2)
    auc = roc_auc_score(ytrue, ypreds)
    metrics = {'conf_mtx': conf_mtx,
               'accuracy': accy,
               'auc': auc,
               'recall': recall,
               'precision': precision,
               'f1_score': f1_score,
               'f2_score': f2_score}
    return metrics

Function to visualize the dataset in 2D¶

Used Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to reduce the dimension of the dataset from 20 features to 2 components to visualize the data.

In the first plot below, there are very few minority class samples (brown), and there is no clear separation in the plot between functional and non-functional samples.

The second plot shows that, although the classes are still not easily separable, there are more minority samples, so in theory a model will be better able to learn the patterns that exist and identify minority samples more effectively.

We recognize that these plots highlight the potential outliers in this dataset. We did check for outliers during EDA, and we tested all models on data with the outliers' values clipped using the first and third quartiles and interquartile range. However, this actually worsened model performance, so we left the outliers alone.

We experimented with simpler methods for dealing with imbalanced classes, such as setting the class weight parameter in a Logistic Regression model to "balanced," or tuning the scale pos weight parameter in an XGBoost model. The better results, however, came from using Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique (SMOTE).

In [21]:
# visualize data in 2D
def show_2D_scatterplot(X, y, title='Data in 2 Dimensions', n_components=2): 
    pca = PCA(n_components=n_components)
    X_new = pca.fit_transform(X)
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
    if n_components == 2:
        plt.scatter(X_new[:,0], X_new[:,1], c=y)
        plt.title(title)
        plt.xlabel('PC1')
        plt.ylabel('PC2')
        plt.show()
    else:
        ax = plt.axes(projection='3d')
        ax.scatter3D(X_new[:,0],X_new[:,1],X_new[:,2] , c=Y)
        plt.show()

Hyperparameter Tuning and Modeling¶

We used 5 different machine learning models with and without oversampling dataset to create a classification model that can predict if the waterpoint is functional or non-functional. At the end, we had 10 models to compare. We are comparing models different matrices as well as time taken to finish the prediction on the test dataset.

  1. XGBoost,
  2. Logistic Regression,
  3. Naive Bayes,
  4. KNN.
  5. Random Forest

The model that outperformed is :

In mostly all the evaluation and performance metrics, the best model is the XGBoost Classifier on the resampled data using SMOTE. Random Forest model came very close with the XGBoost model but as we can see below in the table XGBoost was slightly better than the Random Forest. When using the oversampled data, the classes are balanced, so hyperparameters such as max delta step and scale pos weight did not need to be tuned as with the original data. Hyperparameters that impact overfitting, such as n estimators (the number of learners), max depth (the depth of each learner), and learning rate (this limits the correction applied to each new learner), did have an impact on testing performance with the oversampled data.The optimal hyperparameter values were:

  • n estimators: 200
  • max depth: 5
  • learning rate: 0.3

While maintaining an overall accuracy of ~80.0%, this model identified

  • 40.0% of the non-functional samples and
  • 81.0% of the functional samples (in the testing set)

We expected the XGBoost Classifier to outperform the other modeling techniques, given its proven ability to identify non-linear patterns and classify minority samples accurately, even in highly skewed data such as ours.

One primary benefit of using a model like XGBoost is that there is

  • no need to scale the data,
  • perform feature selection, or
  • reduce dimensionality before training the model.

Although we cleaned the data before model fitting, XGBoost can also perform well when outliers are present and when missing values are included.

The consistent performance of XGBoost is due to the non-linear nature of this classifier and the regularization parameters (both L1 and L2) included in its objective function, which minimize overfitting. Regularization, gradient boosting, tree pruning, and built-in cross-validation, are some of the features that give XGBoost an edge over other classification methods, such as Random Forest and AdaBoost.

Other Model Results:

We built 8 other models with Logistic Regression, Naive Bayes, KNN and Random Forest models with and without oversampling (SMOTE). Resampling did seem to have a positive impact on the performance of most of the models we built. It is reasonable to expect that, being trained on data where less than 15% of the samples come from the minority class, a classifier would have difficulty identifying those minority samples in a testing set. There is simply not enough information available to effectively train the classifier.

When SMOTE was used to balance the data, the impact of overfitting was somewhat lessened. The models had more information to learn from in training and could therefore identify non-functional samples more effectively during testing. The overall performance was still not great, but SMOTE did make a difference.

In [24]:
# functions for fitting model

## IF YOU ARE RUNNING THIS NB ON ARCCGIS PRO, PLEASE REMOVE THE n_jobs PARM AS IT WILL CAUSE MULTIPLE ARCCGIS PRO
## SESSIONS DUE TO THE BUG IN THE PRO. THIS HAS BEEN REPORTED TO ESRI.

def tune_hyperparameters(base_model, grid, X, y, scoring='auc'):

    print('***** Tuning Hyperparameters *****')
    random_model = GridSearchCV(estimator=base_model, param_grid=grid,scoring=scoring, cv=3, n_jobs=-1)
#     random_model = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=base_model, param_distributions=grid, scoring=scoring,
#                                       random_state=30, n_iter=10, cv=3, n_jobs=-1)
    random_model.fit(X, y)
    return random_model.best_params_, random_model.best_score_

def fit_xgb(X, y, scoring='accuracy'):
    xgb_n_estimators = [100, 200, 500, 800]
    xgb_max_depth = [2, 5, 8]
#     xgb_min_child_weight = [1, 5, 9]
    xgb_eta = [0.1, 0.3, 0.4]
#     xgb_gamma = [0, 1, 4]

    xgb_grid = {'n_estimators': xgb_n_estimators,
                'max_depth': xgb_max_depth,
#                 'min_child_weight': xgb_min_child_weight,
                'eta': xgb_eta
#                 'gamma': xgb_gamma
               }
    
    spw = y[y==0].shape[0] / y[y==1].shape[0] # set weight to total_neg / total_pos
    base_model = XGBClassifier(objective='binary:logistic', eval_metric='aucpr', scale_pos_weight=spw)
    best_params, best_score = tune_hyperparameters(base_model, xgb_grid, X, y, scoring=scoring)
    print(f'best params for xgb: {best_params}\n')
    final_model = XGBClassifier(**best_params).fit(X, y)
    return final_model

def fit_lr(X, y, scoring='accuracy'):
    lr_solver = ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear']
    lr_penalty = ['none', 'l1', 'l2', 'elasticnet']
    lr_C = [0.001,0.01,0.1,1,10,100]

    lr_grid = {'solver': lr_solver,
               'penalty': lr_penalty,
               'C': lr_C
               }
    
    base_model = LogisticRegression()
    best_params, best_score = tune_hyperparameters(base_model, lr_grid, X, y, scoring=scoring)
    print(best_params)
    final_model = LogisticRegression(**best_params).fit(X, y)
    return final_model

def fit_nb(X, y, scoring='accuracy'):
    nb_grid = {'var_smoothing': [1e-09, 2e-09]
          }
    base_model = GaussianNB()
    best_params, best_score = tune_hyperparameters(base_model, nb_grid, X, y, scoring=scoring)
    final_model = GaussianNB(**best_params).fit(X, y)
    return final_model

def fit_knn(X, y, scoring='accuracy'):
    knn_neighnors = [5,7,9,11,13,15]
    knn_weights = ['uniform','distance']
    knn_metric = ['minkowski','euclidean','manhattan']

    knn_grid = {'n_neighbors' : knn_neighnors,
                   'weights' : knn_weights,
                   'metric' : knn_metric
               }
    base_model = KNeighborsClassifier()
    best_params, best_score = tune_hyperparameters(base_model, knn_grid, X, y, scoring=scoring)
    final_model = KNeighborsClassifier(**best_params).fit(X, y)
    return final_model

def fit_rf(X, y, scoring='accuracy'):
    n_estimators = [100, 300, 500, 800, 1200]
    max_depth = [5, 8, 15, 25, 30]
    min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10, 15, 100]
    min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 5, 10] 

    rf_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators, 
               'max_depth': max_depth,  
                'min_samples_split':min_samples_split, 
                'min_samples_leaf':min_samples_leaf
              }
    
    base_model = RandomForestClassifier()
    best_params, best_score = tune_hyperparameters(base_model, rf_grid, X, y, scoring=scoring)
    final_model = RandomForestClassifier(**best_params).fit(X, y)
    return final_model

Main custom modeling function to put all the modeling steps together¶

In [25]:
# function to put all steps together
def fit_predict_eval_model(X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, 
                                model='lr', scoring='auc',
                              resample=False, scale=False):
    
    if resample:
        print('***** Oversampling Data *****')
        X_train, y_train = get_oversample(X_train, y_train)
    
    if scale:
        print('***** Scaling Data *****')
        X_train = scale_data(X_train)
        X_test = scale_data(X_test)

        
    print('***** Fitting Model *****')
    if model == 'xgb':
        xgb = fit_xgb(X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring)
        print(f'xgb feature imps: {xgb.feature_importances_}')
        plt.bar(range(len(xgb.feature_importances_)), xgb.feature_importances_)
        plt.show()
        print('***** Getting XGB Predictions *****')
        y_train_preds = xgb.predict(X_train)
        y_test_preds = xgb.predict(X_test)

    elif model == 'lr':
        lr = fit_lr(X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring)
        print('***** Getting Logistic Regression Predictions *****')
        y_train_preds = lr.predict(X_train)
        y_test_preds = lr.predict(X_test)

    elif model == 'knn':
        knn = fit_knn(X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring)
        print('***** Getting KNN Predictions *****')
        y_train_preds = knn.predict(X_train)
        y_test_preds = knn.predict(X_test)

    elif model == 'nb':
        nb = fit_nb(X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring)
        print('***** Getting Naive Bayes Predictions *****')
        y_train_preds = nb.predict(X_train)
        y_test_preds = nb.predict(X_test)
        
    elif model == 'rf':
        rf = fit_rf(X_train, y_train, scoring=scoring)
        print('***** Getting Random Forest Predictions *****')
        y_train_preds = rf.predict(X_train)
        y_test_preds = rf.predict(X_test)
        
    print('***** Getting Performance Metrics *****')
    train_metrics = get_eval_metrics(model, y_train, y_train_preds)
    test_metrics = get_eval_metrics(model, y_test, y_test_preds)
    return train_metrics, test_metrics

XGBoost train test plots¶

In [30]:
def show_f2_train_test_plot(model, X_trn, y_trn, X_tst, y_tst):
    from sklearn.metrics import fbeta_score
    y_trn_preds = model.predict(X_trn)
    y_tst_preds = model.predict(X_tst)
    f2_trn = fbeta_score(y_trn, y_trn_preds, beta=2)
    f2_tst = fbeta_score(y_tst, y_tst_preds, beta=2)
    return f2_trn, f2_tst

n_est_vals = [i*100+1 for i in range(6)]
f2_trn_scores = []
f2_tst_scores = []
for n in n_est_vals:
    model = XGBClassifier(n_estimators=n,
                       max_depth=5,
                       eta=0.4,
                       objective='binary:logistic',
                       eval_metric='aucpr',
                       scale_pos_weight=1).fit(X_train_over, y_train_over)
    f2 = show_f2_train_test_plot(model, X_train_over, y_train_over, X_test, y_test)
    f2_trn_scores.append(f2[0])
    f2_tst_scores.append(f2[1])
In [31]:
plt.plot(n_est_vals, f2_trn_scores, color='blue', label='Training')
plt.plot(n_est_vals, f2_tst_scores, color='green', label='Testing')
plt.title('XGBoost Classifier Performance')
plt.xlabel('Number of Estimators')
plt.ylabel('F2 Score')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Naive Bayes model¶

Naive Bayes is a kind of classifier which uses the Bayes Theorem. It predicts membership probabilities for each class such as the probability that given record or data point belongs to a particular class. The class with the highest probability is considered as the most likely class.

This model was the fastest to run but didnot performed good when we considered Recall, precision and F1 and F2 scores.

Random Forest Model¶

Random forest is a supervised learning algorithm. The "forest" of decision trees is built usually trained with the bagging method. The general idea of the bagging method is that a combination of learning models increases the overall result.

In random forests, there is no need for cross-validation or a separate test set to get an unbiased estimate of the test set error. It is estimated internally, during the run. Each tree is constructed using a different bootstrap sample from the original data. About one-third of the cases are left out of the bootstrap sample and not used in the construction of the kth tree.

We see that it performed as good as as XGboost but took longer to complete. It took 520 mins where XGboost took only 46 mins.

Random Forest with NO oversampling¶

Visualize Confusion Matrix¶

In [5]:
import seaborn as sns
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def plotConfusionMatrix(model,cf_matrix):
    ax =   sns.heatmap(cf_matrix/np.sum(cf_matrix), annot=True, 
            fmt='.2%', cmap='Blues')

    ax.set_title(model);
    ax.set_xlabel('\nPredicted Values')
    ax.set_ylabel('Actual Values ');

    ## Ticket labels - List must be in alphabetical order
    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['Non Functional','Functional'])
    ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['Non Functional','Functional'])

    ## Display the visualization of the Confusion Matrix.
    plt.show()

Evaluation Results:¶

As you can see below, in the oversampled dataset, XGBoost has performed the best when we compared F1, F2 score and Recall. Random Forest model came very close with the XGBoost model but as we can see below in the table XGBoost was slightly better than the Random Forest in evaluation matrices but when we compared the run time then XGBoost is the winner. XGBoost took only 46 mins whereas Random Forest took more than 10 times of XGBoost, Random Forest took 520 mins. We have shown testing results of the dataset on the models below.

As the dataset was unbalanced so we are comparing F1, F2 score with Recall to pick the best performing model.

Recall is a measure of quantity. High recall means that an algorithm returns most of the relevant results (whether or not irrelevant ones are also returned)

F1 score is defined as theharmonic mean between precision and recall. It is used as a statistical measure to rate performance. In other words, an F1-score (from 0 to 9, 0 being lowest and 9 being the highest) is a mean of an individual's performance, based on two factors i.e. precision and recall. The F-score, also called the F1-score, isa measure of a model's accuracy on a dataset.The F-score is a way of combining the precision and recall of the model, and it is defined as the harmonic mean of the model's precision and recall.</i>

Model F1: Non Functional Testing F1: Functional Testing F2: Non Functional Testing F2: Functional Testing Recall: Non Functional Testing Recall: Functional Testing Precision: Non Functional Testing Precision: Functional Testing
XGBoost 0.36 0.82 0.39 0.81 0.41 0.80 0.33 0.85

If we want to compare basic matrix like accuracy then here is the side by side comparision. For unbalanced dataset it is not advisable to take Accuarcy as the evaluation matrix.

General Findings:¶

One challenge that we encountered in analyzing this dataset is the common issue of overfitting. We quickly realized that there was a big difference in performance metrics between training and testing for all models. This discovery led us to tune parameters that can impact overfitting, such as the learning rate (eta) parameter in the XGBoost model and the max_depth in the Random Forest. This shows how essential it is to critically examine each step of the methodology and seek out areas where improvements are possible.

Another observation is that using the RandomizedSearchCV function to tune hyperparameters does not always result in the optimal parameter values. Although Randomized Search saves computation time by selecting a random combination of parameter values to tune instead of testing all combinations, it also leaves the possibility of missing the optimal combination of values for a particular model. For example, when tuning the hyperparameters for the XG-Boost Classifier, RandomizedSearchCV gave sub-optimal values, whereas when we used the Grid Search CV, the performance metrics turned out much better. The same pattern emerged when testing different k values and distance metrics (Euclidean vs. Manhattan) in the KNN models. RandomizedSearchCV consistently picked a low k-value, which led to some extreme overfitting. This shows how essential it is to critically examine each step of the methodology and seek out areas where improvements are possible.

Generally, we are satisfied with the performance of the XGBoost Classifier, especially in comparison with the other models. It achieves a reasonable balance between identifying non-functional water points without misidentifying too many functional water points. Still, there is always room for improvement. If we were to continue with this project, we would go back to the text features from the original dataset and do further analysis using Natural Language Processing. There may be patterns in the text that are not detectable with the feature engineering strategies that we used. It is possible that further text analysis, and other techniques might make it possible to capture more of the relationship among the features and the target variable.
